    {"children":[{"checked":null,"children":[{"children":[{"children":[{"type":"text","value":"死了"}],"type":"strong"},{"type":"text","value":" (sǐ le) - \"died; is dead\""}],"type":"paragraph"}],"spread":false,"type":"listItem"},{"checked":null,"children":[{"children":[{"children":[{"type":"text","value":"死人"}],"type":"strong"},{"type":"text","value":" (sǐrén) - \"dead person\""}],"type":"paragraph"}],"spread":false,"type":"listItem"},{"checked":null,"children":[{"children":[{"children":[{"type":"text","value":"生死"}],"type":"strong"},{"type":"text","value":" (shēngsǐ) - \"life and death\""}],"type":"paragraph"}],"spread":false,"type":"listItem"},{"checked":null,"children":[{"children":[{"children":[{"type":"text","value":"死心"}],"type":"strong"},{"type":"text","value":" (sǐxīn) - \"give up hope; lose heart\""}],"type":"paragraph"}],"spread":false,"type":"listItem"},{"checked":null,"children":[{"children":[{"children":[{"type":"text","value":"死记"}],"type":"strong"},{"type":"text","value":" (sǐjì) - \"memorize by rote\" (literally \"dead memorize\")"}],"type":"paragraph"}],"spread":false,"type":"listItem"}],"ordered":false,"spread":false,"start":null,"type":"list"},
    {"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Cultural Context"}],"depth":2,"type":"heading"},
    {"children":[{"type":"text","value":"In Chinese culture, 死 is often avoided in direct conversation due to cultural taboos around death.\nMany euphemisms are used instead. However, 死 appears in many idioms and expressions where it\nemphasizes extremes or completeness, such as 死记硬背 (rote memorization) or 累死了 (extremely\ntired). The concept is treated with reverence and respect in traditional Chinese culture."}],"type":"paragraph"}
